    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-10T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-10T09:00:00-05:00" n="594"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d594">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5231/1038: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-10T14:00:00+00:00"
                            >October 10, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 10—12:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>68. Your No. 67, October 9, 6 p.m. I am well aware of activities of American firm
                    in question. In recent informal interview with Pan, however, he was informed
                    that we cannot even discuss loan pending completion of the treaty under
                    negotiations and he expressed himself in complete accord with our view that
                    treaty and possible loan must be kept entirely separate.</p>
                <p>Despatch No. 913, October 8th<note n="23" xml:id="d594fn23">Not printed.</note>
                    describing conversation with Pan and enclosing memorandum on possible loan
                    mailed in yesterday’s pouch.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
